#

# Scales and coordinate systems in **ggplot2**

## Getting the data

::: {.small-font}
The `boxoffice` dataset:
:::

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
boxoffice <- tibble(
  rank = 1:5,
  title = c("Star Wars", "Jumanji", "Pitch Perfect 3", "Greatest Showman", "Ferdinand"),
  amount = c(71.57, 36.17, 19.93, 8.81, 7.32) # million USD
)
```
:::



:::

::: {.fragment}
::: {.small-font}
The `tx_counties` dataset:
:::

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
tx_counties <- read_csv("https://wilkelab.org/DSC385/datasets/US_census.csv") |> 
  filter(state == "Texas") |>
  mutate(popratio = pop2010/median(pop2010)) |>
  arrange(desc(popratio)) |>
  mutate(index = 1:n())
```
:::



:::
:::

## Getting the data

::: {.small-font}
The `temperatures` and `temps_wide` datasets (long and wide format of the same data):
:::

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# long format
temperatures <- read_csv("https://wilkelab.org/DSC385/datasets/tempnormals.csv") |>
  mutate(
    location = factor(
      location, levels = c("Death Valley", "Houston", "San Diego", "Chicago")
    )
  ) |>
  select(location, station_id, day_of_year, month, temperature)

# wide format
temps_wide <- temperatures |>
  pivot_wider(
    id_cols = c("month", "day_of_year"),
    names_from = "location", values_from = "temperature"
  )
```
:::



:::

## Scale functions customize the x and y axes

Recall the box-office example from a prior lecture:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell output-location='column'}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(boxoffice) +
  aes(amount, fct_reorder(title, amount)) +
  geom_col()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/boxoffice-scale-progression1-1.svg)
:::
:::



:::

## Scale functions customize the x and y axes

Add scale functions (no change in figure so far):

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell output-location='column'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="4-5"}
ggplot(boxoffice) +
  aes(amount, fct_reorder(title, amount)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_x_continuous() +
  scale_y_discrete()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/boxoffice-scale-progression2-1.svg)
:::
:::



:::

## Scale functions customize the x and y axes

The parameter `name` sets the axis title:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell output-location='column'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="5,8"}
ggplot(boxoffice) +
  aes(amount, fct_reorder(title, amount)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "weekend gross (million USD)"
  ) +
  scale_y_discrete(
    name = NULL  # no axis title
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/boxoffice-scale-progression3-1.svg)
:::
:::



:::

::: {.fragment}
Note: We could do the same with `xlab()` and `ylab()`
:::


## Scale functions customize the x and y axes

The parameter `limits` sets the scale limits:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell output-location='column'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="6"}
ggplot(boxoffice) +
  aes(amount, fct_reorder(title, amount)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "weekend gross (million USD)",
    limits = c(0, 80)
  ) +
  scale_y_discrete(
    name = NULL
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/boxoffice-scale-progression4-1.svg)
:::
:::



:::

::: {.fragment}
Note: We could do the same with `xlim()` and `ylim()` but I advise against it, as these functions can have unexpected side-effects
:::


## Scale functions customize the x and y axes

The parameter `breaks` sets the axis tick positions:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell output-location='column'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="7"}
ggplot(boxoffice) +
  aes(amount, fct_reorder(title, amount)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "weekend gross (million USD)",
    limits = c(0, 80),
    breaks = c(0, 25, 50, 75)
  ) +
  scale_y_discrete(
    name = NULL
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/boxoffice-scale-progression5-1.svg)
:::
:::



:::

## Scale functions customize the x and y axes

The parameter `labels` sets the axis tick labels:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell output-location='column'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="8"}
ggplot(boxoffice) +
  aes(amount, fct_reorder(title, amount)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "weekend gross (million USD)",
    limits = c(0, 80),
    breaks = c(0, 25, 50, 75),
    labels = c("0", "$25M", "$50M", "$75M")
  ) +
  scale_y_discrete(
    name = NULL
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/boxoffice-scale-progression6-1.svg)
:::
:::



:::

## Scale functions customize the x and y axes

The parameter `expand` sets the axis expansion:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell output-location='column'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="9"}
ggplot(boxoffice) +
  aes(amount, fct_reorder(title, amount)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "weekend gross (million USD)",
    limits = c(0, 80),
    breaks = c(0, 25, 50, 75),
    labels = c("0", "$25M", "$50M", "$75M"),
    expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.06))
  ) +
  scale_y_discrete(
    name = NULL
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/boxoffice-scale-progression7-1.svg)
:::
:::



:::

## Scale functions define transformations

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="50%"}
Linear y scale:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="4"}
ggplot(tx_counties) +
  aes(x = index, y = popratio) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous() 
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/tx-counties-ggplot-linear-1.svg){width=90%}
:::
:::



:::
:::

::: {.fragment .column width="50%"}
Log y scale:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="4"}
ggplot(tx_counties) +
  aes(x = index, y = popratio) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/tx-counties-ggplot-log-1.svg){width=90%}
:::
:::



:::
:::

:::

## Parameters work the same for all scale functions

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="50%"}
Linear y scale:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="5-7"}
ggplot(tx_counties) +
  aes(x = index, y = popratio) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "population number / median",
    breaks = c(0, 100, 200),
    labels = c("0", "100", "200")
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/tx-counties-ggplot-linear2-1.svg){width=90%}
:::
:::



:::
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
Log y scale:

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="5-7"}
ggplot(tx_counties) +
  aes(x = index, y = popratio) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10(
    name = "population number / median",
    breaks = c(0.01, 1, 100),
    labels = c("0.01", "1", "100")
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/tx-counties-ggplot-log2-1.svg){width=90%}
:::
:::



:::
:::

:::

## Coords define the coordinate system

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(temperatures, aes(day_of_year, temperature, color = location)) +
  geom_line() +
  coord_cartesian()  # cartesian coords are the default
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/temperatures-cartesian-1.svg){width=60%}
:::
:::



:::

## Coords define the coordinate system

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="3"}
ggplot(temperatures, aes(day_of_year, temperature, color = location)) +
  geom_line() +
  coord_polar()   # polar coords
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/temperatures-polar-1.svg){width=60%}
:::
:::



:::

## Coords define the coordinate system

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="4"}
ggplot(temperatures, aes(day_of_year, temperature, color = location)) +
  geom_line() +
  coord_polar() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 105))  # fix up temperature limits
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/temperatures-polar2-1.svg){width=60%}
:::
:::



:::


## Use `coord_fixed()` for fixed aspect ratio

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(temps_wide, aes(`San Diego`, Houston)) +
  geom_path()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/axis-scaling-bad-1.svg){width=60%}
:::
:::



:::

::: {.small-font .move-up-1em}
(Bad, x and y axis show the same values scaled differently)
:::

## Use `coord_fixed()` for fixed aspect ratio

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(temps_wide, aes(`San Diego`, Houston)) +
  geom_path() +
  coord_fixed()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/axis-scaling-good-1.svg){width=60%}
:::
:::



:::

::: {.small-font .move-up-1em}
(Better, x and y axis are now scaled the same)
:::


## Use `coord_fixed()` for fixed aspect ratio

::: {.smaller-font}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(temps_wide, aes(`San Diego`, Houston)) +
  geom_path() +
  coord_fixed() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(50, 60, 70), limits = c(50, 75))
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![&nbsp;](coordinate-systems-axes_files/figure-revealjs/axis-scaling-good2-1.svg){width=60%}
:::
:::



:::

::: {.small-font .move-up-1em}
(Even better, similar axis ticks along both axes)
:::


